<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB REF="034111_0005_0FFA8A556E1C2F18">
<HEAD>ALL IN A BUSTLE: OR THE NEW HOUSE.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Scene, the Stage, ju&s;t before the doors of the theatre open.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter the</HI> Prompter <HI>and</HI> Jingle.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prompter.</SPEAKER>
<P>SIR Mr. Hodgkin&s;on will be here directly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jingle.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hodgkin&s;on is a good &s;tudy is not he?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prom.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nobody quicker &s;ir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Glad of it&mdash;have a few lines here to open the theatre, will immortalize him&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prom.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir he is prepared with an addre&s;s</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poo&mdash;mere make &s;hift&mdash;becau&s;e nothing better was offered him&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prom.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am told it is a good thing &s;ir&mdash;written by a gentleman of approved ta&s;te&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mum for that&mdash;not one new idea&mdash;lay my exi&s;t|ence of it&mdash;the&s;e things are out of your Sphere Mr. Promp|ter&mdash;let him once &s;ee mine&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prom.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here he comes &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Enter the Manager.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manager.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Prompter&mdash;come&mdash;bu&s;tle&mdash;we have not a moment to &s;pare&mdash;who is that? <HI>(a&s;ide)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prom.</SPEAKER>
<P>A gentleman has brought you &s;ome lines to open the theatre with</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn his lines.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="4" REF="034111_0006_0FFA8A5710BC9B60">
<SPEAKER>Prom.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;let the audience do that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir&mdash;your mo&s;t obedient&mdash;Mr. Hodgkin&s;on I pre&s;ume&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>At your &s;ervice &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir&mdash;<HI>(takes his hand)</HI> I congratulate you on the opening this elegant theatre&mdash;I am &s;afely arrived, and know|ing the barrenne&s;s of literary talent in this country&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir you mi&s;take&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh&mdash;pardon me &s;ir&mdash;policy may dictate excu&s;es&mdash;but mum for that&mdash;you know better</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prom.</SPEAKER>
<P>A mode&s;t fellow this <HI>(a&s;ide)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear fellow&mdash;here&mdash;lock your&s;elf up ten minutes and &s;tudy there&mdash;all pith&mdash;none of your coar&s;e frothy &s;tuff&mdash;whipt &s;yllabub every &s;yllable:</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I've&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come&mdash;no excu&s;es&mdash;they'll immortalize you&mdash;I know they'll &s;ucceed&mdash;hark'ye; read them to an old woman of &s;ixty&mdash;Moliere's plan you know&mdash;an old deaf nur&s;e where I board&mdash;liked them va&s;tly&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir I&mdash;(<HI>eagerly</HI>)</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>No apologies between friends&mdash;expen&s;ive e&s;tabli&s;h|ment this&mdash;want good things&mdash;dull &s;tuff wont do&mdash;increa&s;e of company&mdash;lights expen&s;ive&mdash;&s;alaries rai&s;ed&mdash;people's expectations rai&s;ed&mdash;hopes of emolument rai&s;ed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes &s;ir&mdash;and if we &s;tand talking here&mdash;the gods will be upon us before we are ready: and then there will be the devil of a du&s;t rai&s;ed&mdash;about our ears.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Mrs. Hodgkin&s;on.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Hodgkin&s;on, will you be kind enough to direct me to my dre&s;&s;ing room&mdash;for tho' I've been in it two or three times, I cannot find my way to it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go up the &s;tairca&s;e my dear round that cor|ner&mdash;on the &s;econd &s;tory turn to the left, and you will find a flight of &s;tairs; go down them, and yours is the fourth door on the right hand: but be careful which &s;tairca&s;e you go down, for if you take the wrong, you will lo&s;e your&s;elf among the unfini&s;hed apartments&mdash;the prompter will conduct you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="5" REF="034111_0007_0FFA8A59C24037B8">
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here &s;ir&mdash;another jeu d'esprit&mdash;a &s;erious&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I have no lei&s;ure now&mdash;my dear do get rid of this poet for me <HI>(turns away to give orders to the &s;ervants who are bu&s;y with the &s;cenes.)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will (&s;he turns to Jingle) Sir, you will excu&s;e me&mdash;but&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;erious prologue Madam; written in quick mea&s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;erious prologue in quick mea&s;ure! very &s;ingular that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes Madam and a comic epilogue in blank ver&s;e</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>And a comic epilogue in blank ver&s;e! more &s;ingular &s;till.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>You don't &s;ee the propriety of that now</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do not I confe&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm a&s;toni&s;hed&mdash;no, I beg pardon&mdash;I'm not a&s;toni&s;hed: the&s;e are errors that a refined ta&s;te only can correct&mdash;now Madam&mdash;&s;hould not a &s;erious addre&s;s he levelled at the pa&s;&s;ions!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;ince the pa&s;&s;ions are impetuous the attacks &s;hould be violent&mdash;and how can that be accompli&s;hed, but by a rapidity of utterance,&mdash;and what but quick mea&s;ure can trip over the tongue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ingenious at lea&s;t &s;ir, if not convincing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why are you ladies &s;o per&s;ua&s;ive? why have you &s;uch &s;uperior hold over the pa&s;&s;ions? my Dear Madam merely from your volubility.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>From our volubility <HI>only</HI> &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Solely</HI> Madam&mdash;did you ever know a woman capable of &s;itting three minutes comfortably without talking</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have known many &s;uch &s;ir</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;t have been deaf or dumb then</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are very polite &s;ir</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Facts are &s;tubborn things Madam&mdash;Experientia docet; nature fore &s;aw the evil and out of compa&s;&s;ion to the ladies, as &s;he gave them &s;lippery tongues &s;he left them with &s;mooth chins&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="6" REF="034111_0008_0FFA8A5C276720B0">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't under&s;tand you &s;ir</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can't you tell Madam why nature refu&s;ed to give the ladies beards</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Beards Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll tell you Madam&mdash;becau&s;e they can't hold their tongues long enough to be &s;haved</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word &s;ir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>No general rule tho' without an exception&mdash;knew two ladies my&s;elf that had beards&mdash;two old maids, one &s;ixty five, the other &s;eventy&mdash;ea&s;ily accounted for; time who you know is your greate&s;t enemy, had robbed them of their teeth, and to prevent di&s;covery they impo&s;ed &s;ilence on their tongues; they &s;hut them up in perpetual confinement&mdash;&s;ettled a contract between the no&s;e and chin, to make the lips do the regular duty of &s;trict jailors&mdash;as &s;oon as na|ture perceived the danger of talking was over, &s;he became bountiful, and the harve&s;t on their chins made ample com|pen&s;ation for the daurage the mouth had &s;u&s;tained in the lo&s;s of its furniture.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>If your doctrine is true &s;ir, nature was very &s;piteful in furni&s;hing your chin; for if you are always as talkative as at pre&s;ent your wind pipe mu&s;t have been in frequent danger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's right Madam,&mdash;true woman&mdash;retort your foibles upon us&mdash;here, have you been having all the talk to your&s;elf for this half hour</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>I! &s;ir having all the&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>There again&mdash;wont let me put in a word</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>No fear of your having a beard Madam&mdash;<HI>(he &s;ees the manager turns &s;hort round and follows him)</HI> now &s;ir only give me your patient hearing and I will read one of the principal &s;cenes either of a Tragedy, Comedy or Farce&mdash;I have them all about me&mdash;<HI>(takes them out of his pocket pulls out his &s;pectacles and puts them on.)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, it is impo&s;&s;ible&mdash;you &s;ee how I am engag'd&mdash;if you will leave them at my hou&s;e, I will read them the fir&s;t lei&s;ure moment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="7" REF="034111_0009_0FFA8A5EDAABB688">
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Leave them at your hou&s;e! <HI>(&s;tare&s; at him)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes in Fair Street.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>You wrote the launch, Sir didn't you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>I did!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>And you wrote the Man of Fortitude.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I &s;uppo&s;e, after you have detained my plays a mouth or two, you would be writing again?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>M<HI>anag.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Suppo&s;e I &s;hould?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Much obliged to you&mdash;can't leave my plays with any body&mdash;fine thoughts are worth &s;tealing&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, do you &s;u&s;pect!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Know you would&mdash;<HI>(pulls off his &s;pectacles)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir&mdash;<HI>(in a pa&s;&s;ion)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Author can't help it&mdash;do it my&s;elf&mdash;&s;teal half my be&s;t things&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>I dont doubt it&mdash;<HI>(turns away in a pet)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(Turning &s;hort to Mrs. Hodg.)</HI> pick up a good thought Madam&mdash;Strip it of the author's language&mdash;dre&s;s it up in my own&mdash;wiredraw it a little for the advantage of weak judgments&mdash;and boldly claim the merit of originality.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;uch thefts are ea&s;ily detected, &s;ir</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye by one in a thou&s;and&mdash;Madam <HI>thinking</HI> is no part of modern author&s;hip&mdash;the ancients have left us thoughts enough&mdash;all we have to do is to hammer them well, and lay them on like modern plate, as thin as po&s;&s;ible on any cour&s;e materials.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your ingenuity is equal to your politene&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Took all my pieces to a man who has the general character of a connoi&s;&s;eur, but there is no ta&s;te here Madam, would you believe it? he laught at the mo&s;t pathetic parts of my Tragedy; yawn'd and made wry faces during the great|er part of the Comedy, and ab&s;olutely went to &s;leep all the Farce&mdash;there is want of ta&s;te for you Madam&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;ir you had better call on Mr. Hodg|kin&s;on To-morrow? I cannot &s;tay any longer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Take your advice Madam&mdash;but heark ye&mdash;a word
<PB N="8" REF="034111_0010_0FFA8A628CF6E4B8">
in your ear&mdash;he'll be damn'd mad&mdash;that he mi&s;s'd my lines&mdash;the fine&s;t you ever read&mdash;only give me five minutes&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impo&s;&s;ible &s;ir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jin.</SPEAKER>
<P>Adieu&mdash;call and read them to you another time&mdash;but hark'ye &s;han't tru&s;t my pieces out of my own hands&mdash;Sir Fretful Plagiary for that, you under&s;tand me.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Writes him&s;elf!</P>
<STAGE>(Jingle goes out on one &s;ide, the manager enters on the o|ther)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, have you got rid of him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>With &s;ome difficulty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>No matter how&mdash;&s;o he's gone&mdash;Mr. Hughes de&s;ire the &s;tage door keeper to admit no &s;tranger whatever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>I want to try my voice, let us go thro' a &s;hort &s;cene.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>It mu&s;t be a &s;hort one then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll try an invocation to &s;ee whether the un|der tones are di&s;tinct.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do&mdash;and let it be extempore</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Re&s;tore him&mdash;merciful Gods <HI>(looks to the general box)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! ha!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>(Stops &s;hort)</HI> what do you laugh at?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear you forget where you are, you are not addre&s;&s;ing the gods&mdash;that is the general box, the gods are yonder removed at awful di&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>True&mdash;I beg their god&s;hips pardon, well I'll &s;uppo&s;e them there and apologize&mdash;pardon high and mighty gods, nor let your thun'dring vengeance fall upon an humble &s;uppliant for &s;o venial an offence: for tho' my er|ring eye mi&s;took the awful &s;eat of your abode, my a&s;piring heart, on adoration's wings, was &s;oaring to approach you gratefully to thank you for every favour pa&s;t, and humbly to implore your future approbation&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well my dear, very well</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I was to addre&s;s the gods, for one quar|ter
<PB N="9" REF="034111_0011_0FFA8A65742C2BB0">
of an hour, my neck would be &s;o &s;et, that I &s;hould not have the u&s;e of it again for a month.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come then I'll tell you how you may try your voice without breaking your neck.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>How?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why by &s;inging a &s;ong.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Hodg.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart&mdash;</P>
<L>Great Shake&s;peare come! and &s;pread around</L>
<L>Thy magic influence on this ground.</L>
<L>In humble adoration, lo!</L>
<L>We bend the willing knee;</L>
<L>Dear, hollow'd &s;hade, on us be&s;tow</L>
<L>What nature gave to thee:</L>
<L>And when thou deign'st to view from high</L>
<L>Our trembling, thrilling, extacy.</L>
<L>Each ravi&s;h'd &s;oul on wings of fire</L>
<L>Shall ri&s;e thy favour'd choir among.</L>
<L>Hark! hark! 'tis Shake&s;peare &s;trikes the lyre</L>
<L>Stealing nature's &s;weete&s;t &s;ong.</L>
<L>Awake my &s;oul, the&s;e raptures prove,</L>
<L>From none but HIM &s;uch tran&s;ports flow,</L>
<L>His touch can make all bo&s;oms glow,</L>
<L>In&s;piring harmony and love.</L>
<P>and now I'll go and &s;ee if I can find my dre&s;&s;ing room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Take care you don't mi&s;take the &s;lairs.</P>
<STAGE>Exit. Mrs. Hodg. (A noi&s;e behind between the Prompter and O'Flaharty.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Promp.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I tell you Mr. Hodgkin&s;on&mdash;cannot be &s;po|ken with.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Boderation honey <HI>(pu&s;hes on with his wife)</HI> kape your pratty looking daddles off that lady joy&punc; or by my &s;houl I'll&mdash;Oh your &s;arvant &s;ir&mdash;you are not Mr. Hodg|kin&s;on the manager to be &s;ure now are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am&mdash;but&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>I did not gue&s;s that, do you &s;ee now&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="10" REF="034111_0012_0FFA8A6857034410">
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>And pray &s;ir, who are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh!&mdash;to be &s;ure I'm not little Flanagan O'Fla|harty&mdash;ju&s;t landed, comfortably &s;eaked and dry as a &s;alt fi&s;h after a plea&s;ant journey from dear Tipperary.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>And the lady?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh to be &s;ure, &s;he is not my wife honey.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>And your bu&s;ine&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bu&s;ine&s;s joy!&mdash;to be &s;ure you live in America and can't gue&s;s now!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, it is a bu&s;y time&mdash;and I will thank you to tell your bu&s;ine&s;s as briefly as po&s;&s;ible?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>As to our bu&s;ine&s;s, look you joy a man of your di&s;arnment can't &s;ee that with both your eyes &s;hut, why to be &s;ure our bu&s;ine&s;s is not playing my dear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>you are actors then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have hit it honey.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>To deal plainly with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh don't be after complimenting; as to a choice of parts do ye &s;ee&mdash;we're not too delicate on that head! for my own part, look you&mdash;Richard&mdash;Macbeth&mdash;Lare&mdash;Hamlet Benedick&mdash;and a few other &s;uch characters would do to &s;tart with.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir many of tho&s;e characters I fill my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why aye, as you &s;ay&mdash;a New-York audience may have put up with a little make&s;hift&mdash;but let them once &s;ee me, my dare&mdash;and to be &s;ure they won't find out the differ|ence&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh no doubt.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>And then to &s;hew you I'm not unra&s;onable&mdash;you may &s;et me down now&mdash;for Fal&s;taff&mdash;Wapid&mdash;Don Falix&mdash;Romeo and Marplot&mdash;for &s;uch &s;econd rate characters to be &s;ure now little O'Flaharty would not a&s;toni&s;h them&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I tell you &s;ir</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh now&mdash;dont be apologi&s;ing&mdash;my dare&mdash;I would not refu&s;e to play &s;uch paltry characters as paping Tom&mdash;Lingo or even Shelty&mdash;joy&mdash;now to be &s;ure you won't call that condacen&s;ion&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="11" REF="034111_0013_0FFA8A6C1F2B4F20">
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn it &s;ir, I tell you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O. Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>But my dare&mdash;don't be for putting me into any of your characters that have nothing to recommend them but the brogue&mdash;I never could put the damn'd brogue upon my tongue in my life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manager.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O. Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh none of your palaver&mdash;little O' Flaharty, is not to be humbug'd, my dare&mdash;you may give your brogues to tho&s;e who can't &s;peak pure Engli&s;h&mdash;You may play them your&s;elf joy; I'm for your jonteel line honey.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady.</SPEAKER>
<P>And as for me, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>For God's &s;ake, Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady.</SPEAKER>
<P>You may clap me down for Juliet&mdash;Lady Mac|beth&mdash;Beatrice&mdash;Lady Townley&mdash;De&s;demona&mdash;Lady Racket&mdash;Alicia&mdash;and a few of that &s;ort of things.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, once for all, I mu&s;t tell you&mdash;our company is full, and as for ladies, there are more already than I can po&s;&s;ibly find parts to &s;atisfy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now can't you be ea&s;y.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir&mdash;Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, don't be apologizing now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damnation&mdash;here John&mdash;&s;hew this Gentle|man and Lady the door.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<P>Nay Sir&mdash;I have no time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Suppo&s;e I give you a fane in Macbeth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will not be interrupted Sir&mdash;and if you won't leave me, I mu&s;t leave you. <HI>(Going.)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>How damn'd fond you are of talking my dare; but &s;ince you will have all the palaver to your&s;elf, I'll call on you again to-morrow. Your &s;arvant.</P>
<STAGE>(Goes out with his wife.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who the devil would be a manager.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Comes in again.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>One word, honey.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damnation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>You could not lend me five dollars for a few days?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="034111_0014_0FFA8A6EC9288738">
<SPEAKER>Manag,</SPEAKER>
<P>I have <HI>no money</HI> to lend, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'El.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll pay you out of the profits of my benefit, honey.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir I de&s;ire you'll leave me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>What Sir.&mdash;Would you be after putting an af|front upon a jontleman?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Leave me Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, oh, to be &s;ure, little O'Flaharty wont &s;hew you what good breeding is&mdash;if you won't engage me, my dear, you &s;hall &s;ight me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Any thing to get rid of you&mdash;any thing ano|ther time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>O'Fl.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure, I wont &s;how you what a coward is.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Mrs Collins, followed by Mr Prigmore.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Collins.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Mr. Hodgkin&s;on, why am I cant|ed up into a three pair of &s;tairs dre&s;&s;ing room?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Madam, I have done all for the be&s;t, but you &s;ee it is impo&s;&s;ible to plea&s;e every body.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. C.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, if I am to dance up and down three pair of &s;tairs, at every trifling change of dre&s;s where am I to find breath to go thro' my part?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam you mu&s;t be &s;atisfied for to night, at lea&s;t, this is no time to make alterations.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. C.</SPEAKER>
<P>As to that, Sir, I am as &s;oon &s;atisfied as ano|ther; but I don't like partialities.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<P><HI>During this &s;cene, Mr. Prigmore is mea&s;uring the &s;tage, by walking acro&s;s it.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well Prig&mdash;What are you at now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prig.</SPEAKER>
<P>Practi&s;ing the tread of the &s;tage. I expect &s;ome of us, forgetting where we are, &s;hall think we have made our exit, before we have half cro&s;s'd it; for in&s;tance, now in one of my characters&mdash;I am &s;tanding on this &s;ide; four &s;trides, and three &s;quints at the gallery, at the other theatre, carry me completely off&mdash;egad, you &s;ee, here, it would leave me right in the center.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="13" REF="034111_0015_0FFA5F68D9C83458">
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, that would be no bad joke; for you might &s;tand and make pretty faces at the gallery: They love to &s;ee your face, Prig.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prig.</SPEAKER>
<P>Make faces at the gallery, that's a good joke&mdash;why damme, where would be the u&s;e of that: at the other hou&s;e, indeed, a well made up face &s;tood a chance to be noticed: but here, damme, we &s;hall all look like wax-dolls, thro' the dimini&s;hing end of a tele&s;cope.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Mr. Hallam jun.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Hal.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir: Mr. Hogg &s;ays, if the chimney in his dre&s;&s;ing-room is not altered, he &s;hall be &s;moke dried in a month like a &s;ide of bacon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's a pretty piece of gammon for you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Hal.</SPEAKER>
<P>And here's the bill of the coals ju&s;t laid in, Mr. Cant's compliments and you mu&s;t &s;end him the money.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why they an't all deliver'd are they?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. H.</SPEAKER>
<P>The la&s;t load came in this afternoon, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>He is in a confounded hurry, tell him to call on Mr. Dunlap.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>John.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;ays he can't wait, he don't like you player folks&mdash;he won't have dealing with the unrighteous; he has committed a great &s;in in &s;elling coals for &s;uch an ungodly u&s;e, and he fears he &s;hall be read out of the conventicle for it&mdash;he therefore wants the money directly, that he may clo&s;e the affair, and pacify his con&s;cience.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn his con&s;cience&mdash;tell him he &s;hall wait our convenience for his impudence.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit Mr. H.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Mr. John&s;on.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. John&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Hodgkin&s;on, do you know that it is within half an hour of the time to open the doors.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;and every body is in a bu&s;tle and no|body ready.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<P><HI>Mrs. John&s;on above behind the &s;cenes, calls loud, as in a fright.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. John&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. John&s;on! Mr. John&s;on!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="14" REF="034111_0016_0FFA8A73C3C18088">
<SPEAKER>John&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark!&mdash;was not that Mrs. John&s;on's voice?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>It &s;ounded like it&mdash;where can &s;he be?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. John&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. John&s;on! <HI>(calling again.)</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. John&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>My God, is that you&mdash;where are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. John&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. John&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here! where?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. John&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know&mdash;I have lo&s;t my&s;elf&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. John&s;on.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lo&s;t your&s;elf&mdash;ble&s;s my &s;oul!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! ha!&mdash;there &s;he is, in the upper carpenter's gallery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. John.</SPEAKER>
<P>How the plague could &s;he get there.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Prompter.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Prompter.</SPEAKER>
<P>If the carpenters don't alter tho&s;e bells I &s;hall never be able to give the thunder and lightning proper warning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then Sir, why did not you look after tho&s;e things in time.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Mr. Lee.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Lee</SPEAKER>
<P>Where am I to put all the&s;e properties, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why in the property room to be &s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Lee</SPEAKER>
<P>The property room is full of carpenter's lum|ber, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, don't plague me about it ju&s;t now, put them any where for the pre&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Mr. Jeffer&s;on.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Jeff.</SPEAKER>
<P>All is in confu&s;ion above, Sir. the &s;ky and the &s;ea have run foul of each other&mdash;the garden &s;cene has got entangled over the clouds! and trying to get them loo&s;e the gla&s;s in the green-hou&s;e has cut off the horns of the new moon, and &s;cratched the clouds &s;o that they look like flying dumplings.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why what the devil has got into the people&mdash;where are the painters and machini&s;ts that they don't look better after things?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="15" REF="034111_0017_0FFA8A7796592548">
<SPEAKER>Mr. Jeff.</SPEAKER>
<P>They complain that &s;o many people go a|bove, they are perpetually hindered, and if a &s;top is not put to it, every thing will be &s;poil'd&mdash;The black wench that at|tends the three pair of &s;tairs dre&s;&s;ing room, has been walk|ing over the new clouds and left all the marks of her feet upon them, &s;he took her&s;elf for Juno I &s;uppo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll make her find out &s;he is more like Belze|bub.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Jeff.</SPEAKER>
<P>The clouds not being dry down &s;he &s;lipt and mea&s;ur'd her whole length&mdash;&s;meared the &s;even &s;tars and &s;wept away half the full moon with her petticoats; in &s;crambling to get up &s;he &s;cratched the new Comet &s;o unmercifully that it looks like a worn out traveller ju&s;t arrived off a 500 years journey&mdash;talk of Juno&mdash;Juno never did &s;o much mi&s;|chief in the heavens with all her &s;pite as that wench has done by accident.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why don't they kick every body down &s;tairs that has no bu&s;ine&s;s there?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Jeff.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;ir, there was Mi&s;s Harding and little Sam Stockwell when I came down, making a &s;leigh of Juno's cele&s;tial Car, which Cicery has ju&s;t fini&s;h'd painting.</P>
<STAGE>(A great &s;cream is heard and the Car is let down)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>What the devil's the matter now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stockw.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Carpenters have loo&s;ened the cords and let us down &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Jeff.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thy &s;erv'd you right&mdash;you had no bu&s;ine&s;s there, fa&s;ten the cords Carpenters, leave them where they are till I liberate them&mdash;I'll teach them to go a &s;leighing in the clouds.</P>
<STAGE>(One of the Carpenters calls out from the upper gallery to another below on the oppo&s;ite &s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Carp.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hallo&mdash;Jack.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Carp.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do you want.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Carp.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pull the rope belonging to that tackle between the fir&s;t and &s;econd entrance&mdash;pull it hard and make ha&s;te, &s;ome
<PB N="16" REF="034111_0018_0FFA8A7A415483E0">
of the gentlemen are waiting for the trunk fa&s;tened to the end of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Carp.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll trundle it up to you in a jiffy&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(He takes the wrong rope and rings the great bell violently)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>What the devil are you at now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Jeff.</SPEAKER>
<P>The thick headed booby has got hold of the bell rope in&s;tead of the tackle rope.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do my dear fellow, go and &s;top his noi&s;e.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit. Jeff.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Enter Mr. Martin.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well Jack what's the news with you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Mart.</SPEAKER>
<P>I've been looking after tho&s;e things and no|&s;eems to be right,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Right&mdash;why damn me nothing can be right here, every body &s;eems to be doing every thing but what they ought to do&mdash;the Theatre is like the Tower of Babel, there's nothing but confu&s;ion of tongues in it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Mart.</SPEAKER>
<P>As the porter was bringing St. Pauls Church upon his &s;houlder, the clum&s;y dog ran it thro' an Apotheca|ries window and broke a number of &s;how gla&s;&s;es&mdash;there &s;ir St. Paul lies in the &s;hop drenched in phy&s;ic, and the apothe|cary &s;wears he will keep St. Paul as a pledge; till you pay the damage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll forfeit the carele&s;s ra&s;cal for it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Mart.</SPEAKER>
<P>And then here's the rain, is &s;o dry it rattles no louder than a fall of &s;now&mdash;and the lightning is &s;o damp it wont fla&s;h, and the thunder is out of order, it makes no more noi&s;e than a gentle zephyr, &s;o I &s;ent Tom for the old thun|der from the other hou&s;e, his foot &s;lipt, the lightning got &s;cattered about and is &s;o wet that you might as well try to fla&s;h with a &s;now-ball, the thunder-balls roll'd down a cellar kitchen over&s;et a black woman's child and tumbled into the teawater ca&s;k, her hu&s;band &s;wore the owner of the thunder &s;hould pay for the water, for his wife's tongue was too turbulent already, and he'd be dam'd before &s;he &s;hould drink thunder water; upon this his wife &s;napt her fingers at
<PB N="17" REF="034111_0019_0FFA8A7BE0EA9ED8">
him, dipt a quart mug into it and drank it off, threw a &s;econd into her hu&s;band's face&mdash;cur&s;ed him for a &s;neaking blockhead, kick'd one of the thunder balls again&s;t his &s;hins, and threw a handful of lightning in his eyes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<P><HI>A great &s;cream is heard behind.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>What next?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Mr. Jeffer&s;on, laughing.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's in the wind now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Jeff.</SPEAKER>
<P>One of the ladies, I won't mention names, dre&s;&s;ing her hair, her <HI>wig</HI> I mean, laid it down nicely fi|ni&s;hed on a chair; who &s;hould &s;neak in but <HI>Chance,</HI> Mr. Cooper's dog, and the mi&s;chievous cur taking a fancy to it, walk'd off with it; the lady &s;cream'd, Chance took to his heels, and the dre&s;&s;ers are now in full chace after him to re|cover the &s;tolen property.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Mr. Tyler.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Tyler.</SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;prings of that trap, the man &s;ays, are &s;o weak, that the fir&s;t gho&s;t that a&s;cends, will &s;tand a chance to break his neck.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear fellow, that can't be, we'll call the man, and examine it&mdash;here John, tell the carpenters to open that trap door.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>The trap-door opens and as they are looking down Mrs. Tyler calls out below.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Tyler.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Hodgkin&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>What now, the theatre's haunted, I believe&mdash;above, below, we are attacked in every direction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Tyler.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is Mrs. Tyler's gho&s;t, I believe, by the voice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>It comes from below &s;ure enough what can &s;he be doing there?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Tyler.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Hodgkin&s;on, for God's &s;ake, &s;end &s;omebody to get me out.</P>
<STAGE>(He looks down and &s;ees her.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Get you out Madam! how in the name of wonder got you in.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="18" REF="034111_0020_0FFA8A7EACB21F98">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Tyler.</SPEAKER>
<P>Coming from my dre&s;&s;ing room, I mi&s;&s;ed my way I &s;uppo&s;e, for in&s;tead of getting on the &s;tage, I have found my way under it, you &s;ee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prompter, ring the bell for the trap. <HI>(A&s;ide.) The bell rings and the trap comes up with her upon it.</HI> There Tyler, do you think it will bear a gho&s;t now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Tyler.</SPEAKER>
<P>All my doubts have vani&s;h'd.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Prompter.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Promp.</SPEAKER>
<P>The doors are opening, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Down with the curtain then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Tyler.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye&mdash;or like Samp&s;on, the Phili&s;tines will be upon us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Manag.</SPEAKER>
<P>Every one to his dre&s;&s;ing room, I'll ju&s;t wel|come our old friends in our new hou&s;e, and then follow you.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit all except the Manager.)</STAGE>
<LG>
<L>May <HI>your</HI> brows, oh ye <HI>Fair,</HI> ne'er with &s;orrow be clouded,</L>
<L>And <HI>our</HI> efforts to plea&s;e, keep our <HI>boxes</HI> thus crouded;</L>
<L>May <HI>you,</HI> oh ye critics, abounding with out,</L>
<L>Nightly prai&s;e our attempts from an o'erflowing pit;</L>
<L>Above all, O, ye Gods, we implore without raillery</L>
<L>That your &s;miles and half dollars &s;upport our new gallery;</L>
<L>Our be&s;t talents and time we devote to your will,</L>
<L>That you in return may our trea&s;ury fill;</L>
<L>May our errors &s;till meet with your quick ab&s;olution,</L>
<L>And this theatre thrive like the New Con&s;titution.</L>
</LG>
</SP>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
